install the SELinux packages and configure SELinux to be **disabled after the next reboot
ssh banner@stapp03

Install the required packages:
sudo yum install -y selinux-policy selinux-policy-targeted policycoreutils

on newer RHEL-based systems:
sudo dnf install -y selinux-policy selinux-policy-targeted policycoreutils

Then permanently disable SELinux by editing `/etc/selinux/config`:
sudo sed -i 's/^SELINUX=.*/SELINUX=disabled/' /etc/selinux/config

Verify:
cat /etc/selinux/config | gre -i disa

Expected output:
SELINUX=disabled

Do **not** reboot the server. The current runtime status can remain unchanged. The task only requires that SELinux be configured to come up **disabled after the scheduled reboot**.
